ROC Analysis for Diabetes

Ching Yi Lam

10/25/2024

1 Introduction

We want to see if there is/are any variable(s) will cause the diabetes. We have 9 variables in our dataset. One of the variable is diabetes which indicates if the person has diabetes or not.

1.1 Questions to think of for this dataset

  1. Is the gender correlated to diabetes?

  2. Is age correlated to diabetes? If age will be a possible chance to cause diabetes such as if the person is older that will be a higher chance to have diabetes.

  3. Is history of heart disease correlated to diabetes?

  4. Is smoking history correlated to diabetes?

  5. Is it possible that the higher BMI, the higher chance to have diabetes?

  6. Is blood glucose level correlated to diabetes?

2 Description of Data

The Diabetes prediction dataset comprises medical and demographic information from patients, along with their diabetes diagnosis status which is positive or negative. It includes features such as age, gender, body mass index (BMI), hypertension, heart disease, smoking history, HbA1c levels, and blood glucose levels. This data set is collected from my professor’s teaching data repository. This dataset has 100000 records and 9 variables. All of the variables do not have missing value. A detailed description of the variables is given below:

Gender: Gender refers to the biological sex of the individual: Female, Male, and Other.

Age: Age ranges from 0-80 for the individual in our dataset.

Hypertension: Hypertension is a health condition characterized by consistently high blood pressure in the arteries. 0 indicates they do not have hypertension, and 1 indicates they have hypertension.

Heart_disease: Heart disease is a medical condition linked to a higher risk of developing diabetes. 0 indicates they do not have heart disease, and 1 indicates they have heart disease.

Smoking_history: Smoking history is also regarded as a risk factor for diabetes and can worsen complications related to the condition. We have 5 categories in our dataset: not current, former, no info, current, and never and ever.

BMI: Body Mass Index (BMI) is an indicator of body fat derived from a person’s weight and height. Elevated BMI values are associated with an increased risk of diabetes. The range of BMI in this dataset is from 10.16 to 71.55. BMI less than 18.5 is underweight, 18.5-24.9 is normal, 25-29.9 is overweight, and 30 or more is obese.

HbA1c_level: HbA1c (Hemoglobin A1c) level reflects a person’s average blood sugar over the past 2 to 3 months. Higher HbA1c levels signify a higher risk of developing diabetes. Mostly more than 6.5% of HbA1c level indicates diabetes.

Blood_glucose_level: Blood glucose level indicates the concentration of glucose in the bloodstream at a specific moment. Higher blood glucose levels are a primary indicator of diabetes.

Diabetes: Diabetes is the target variable being predicted. 0 indicates the absence of diabetes, and 1 indicates the presence of diabetes.

A copy of this publicly available data is stored at https://pengdsci.github.io/datasets/bin-DiabetesPred/diabetes_prediction_dataset.csv.

3 Logistic Regression Analysis

The purpose of the logistic regression analysis is to find out if we can use the predictor variables to predict our response variable: Diabetes. The purpose of this analysis will be a predictive analysis.

The response variable: Diabetes

Predictor variables:

  • Gender ID = Gender: 1 = Female, 2 = Male, 3 = Other.
  • Age
  • Hypertension
  • Heart Disease
  • Smoking History ID = Smoking History: 1 = Current, 2 = Ever, 3 = Former, 4 = Never, 5 = No Info.
  • BMI
  • HbA1c Level
  • Blood Glucose Level

Here below we are trying to build the initial model.

  • Build an Initial Model

First, we build a logistic regression model that contains all predictor variables in the dataset. This model called the full model.

# We create the ID variable to build our model.
diabetes$genderID <- as.numeric(diabetes$gender)
diabetes$smoking_historyID <- as.numeric(diabetes$smoking_history)
initial.model = glm(diabetes ~ genderID + age + hypertension + heart_disease + smoking_historyID
                    + bmi + HbA1c_level + blood_glucose_level, family = binomial, data = diabetes)
coefficient.table = summary(initial.model)$coef

All of the p-value for the variables are less than alpha = 0.05. Next, we search for the best model using automatic variable procedure to search the final model.

  • Automatic Variable Selection

The age, BMI and blood glucose level are practically important, we will include these three variables in the final model regardless of the statistical significance.

In summary, we define two models: the full model and the reduced model. The final optimal model will be chosen between these two models. A summary table of the significant tests is provided below.

full.model = initial.model 
reduced.model = glm(diabetes ~ age + bmi + blood_glucose_level , family = binomial, data = diabetes)
backward.model =  step(full.model, 
                    scope=list(lower=formula(reduced.model),upper=formula(full.model)),
                    data = diabetes, 
                    direction = "backward",
                    trace = 0) 
final.model.coef = summary(backward.model)$coef
kable(final.model.coef , caption = "Summary table of significant tests")

4 Subsetting and Scaling Data

Because the boxplot for BMI and blood glucose level are skewed to the right, we use min-max scaling method to scale all the numerical variables in the dataset.

## feature scaling
diabetes$BMIscale = (diabetes$bmi-min(diabetes$bmi))/(max(diabetes$bmi) - min(diabetes$bmi))

diabetes$HbA1c_levelscale = (diabetes$HbA1c_level-min(diabetes$HbA1c_level))/(max(diabetes$HbA1c_level) - min(diabetes$HbA1c_level))

diabetes$agescale = (diabetes$age-min(diabetes$age))/(max(diabetes$age) - min(diabetes$age)) 

diabetes$glucosescale = (diabetes$blood_glucose_level-min(diabetes$blood_glucose_level))/(max(diabetes$blood_glucose_level) - min(diabetes$blood_glucose_level))

7 ROC Analysis for Decision Tree Algorithms

We will set up a random split approach.

# We use a random split approach
n = dim(diabetes)[1]  # sample size
# caution: using without replacement
train.id = sample(1:n, round(0.7*n), replace = FALSE)  
train = diabetes[train.id, ]    # training data
test = diabetes[-train.id, ]    # testing data

7.1 Model of Decision Tree

Here, we create a wrapper to build different decision trees.

# arguments to pass into rpart():
# 1. data set (training /testing); 
# 2. Penalty coefficients
# 3. Impurity measure
## 
tree.builder = function(in.data, fp, fn, purity){
   tree = rpart(diabetes ~ .,                # including all features
                data = in.data, 
                na.action  = na.rpart,       # By default, deleted if the outcome is missing, 
                                             # kept if predictors are missing
                method = "class",            # Classification form factor
                model  = FALSE,
                x = FALSE,
                y = TRUE,
            parms = list( # loss matrix. Penalize false positives or negatives more heavily
                         loss = matrix(c(0, fp, fn, 0), ncol = 2, byrow = TRUE),   
                         split = purity),          # "gini" or "information"
             ## rpart algorithm options (These are defaults)
             control = rpart.control(
                        minsplit = 10,  # minimum number of observations required before split
                        minbucket= 10,  # minimum number of observations in 
                                        # any terminal node, default = minsplit/3
                        cp  = 0.01,  # complexity parameter for stopping rule, 
                                     # 0.02 -> small tree 
                       xval = 10     # number of cross-validation )
                        )
             )
  }

Using the above function, we define six different decision tree models in the following.

  • Model 1: gini.tree.11 is based on the Gini index without penalizing false positives and false negatives.

  • Model 2: into.tree.11 is based on the entropy without penalizing false positives and false negatives.

  • Model 3: gini.tree.1.10 is based on the Gini index with the cost of false positive is 1 and false negative is 10.

  • Model 4: into.tree.1.10 is based on the entropy with the cost of false positive is 1 and false negative is 10.

  • Model 5: gini.tree.10.1 is based on the Gini index with the cost of false positive is 10 and false negative is 1.

  • Model 6: into.tree.10.1 is based on the entropy with the cost of false positive is 10 and false negative is 1.

The tree diagram of Model 1 and Model 2 is shown below.

7.2 ROC for Model Selection

Previously, we built six different decision tree models. Next, we use ROC analysis to identify the best model out of the six candidates.

# function returning a sensitivity and specificity matrix
SenSpe = function(in.data, fp, fn, purity){
  cutoff = seq(0,1, length = 20)   # 20 cut-offs including 0 and 1. 
  model = tree.builder(in.data, fp, fn, purity) 
  ## Caution: decision tree returns both "success" and "failure" probabilities.
  ## We need only "success" probability to define sensitivity and specificity!!! 
  pred = predict(model, newdata = in.data, type = "prob") # two-column matrix.
  senspe.mtx = matrix(0, ncol = length(cutoff), nrow= 2, byrow = FALSE)
  for (i in 1:length(cutoff)){
  # CAUTION: "1" and "0" are values of the label in this data set!
  # The following line uses only "1" probability: pred[, "1"] !!!!
  pred.out =  ifelse(pred[,"1"] >= cutoff[i], "1", "0")  
  TP = sum(pred.out =="1" & in.data$diabetes == "1")
  TN = sum(pred.out =="0" & in.data$diabetes == "0")
  FP = sum(pred.out =="1" & in.data$diabetes == "0")
  FN = sum(pred.out =="0" & in.data$diabetes == "1")
  senspe.mtx[1,i] = TP/(TP + FN)
  senspe.mtx[2,i] = TN/(TN + FP)
  }
  ## A better approx of ROC, need library {pROC}
  prediction = pred[, "1"]
  category = in.data$diabetes == "1"
  ROCobj <- roc(category, prediction)
  AUC = auc(ROCobj)
  ##
  list(senspe.mtx= senspe.mtx, AUC = round(AUC,3))
 }

The function above includes three arguments that allow users to select various types of decision trees, including the six discussed in the previous subsection. Then, we use this function to construct six different tress and plot their corresponding ROC curves to assess the overall performance of these tree algorithms.

8 ROC Analysis for BAGGING Algorithms

In this section, we will have the ROC Analysis for BAGGING algorithms.

##
Diabetes.bag.train <- bagging(as.factor(diabetes) ~ ., 
                              data = train, 
                              nbagg = 150,    # number of trees
                              coob = TRUE, 
                              parms = list(loss = matrix(c(0, 10, 1, 0), 
                                                          ncol = 20, 
                                                          byrow = TRUE),   
                                                          split = "gini"),  
                              control = rpart.control(minsplit = 10, 
                                                      cp = 0.02))
### predict() returns either "class" or "prob" in the classification
### When specifying type = "class", the default cut-off of 0.5 is used.
pred = predict(Diabetes.bag.train, train, type = "prob")
### Optimal cut-off probability identification: no cross-validation is needed
cut.prob = seq(0,1, length = 20)
  senspe.mtx = matrix(0, ncol = length(cut.prob), nrow= 3, byrow = FALSE)
  for (i in 1:length(cut.prob)){
  # CAUTION: "1" and "0" are values of the label in this data set!
  # The following line uses only "1" probability: pred[, "1"] !!!!
  pred.out =  ifelse(pred[,"1"] >= cut.prob[i], "1", "0")  
  TP = sum(pred.out =="1" & train$diabetes == "1")
  TN = sum(pred.out =="0" & train$diabetes == "0")
  FP = sum(pred.out =="1" & train$diabetes == "0")
  FN = sum(pred.out =="0" & train$diabetes == "1")
  senspe.mtx[1,i] = TP/(TP + FN)                  # sensitivity
  senspe.mtx[2,i] = TN/(TN + FP)                  # specificity
  senspe.mtx[3,i] = (TP+TN)/(TP + FN + TN + FP)   # accuracy
  }
  ## A better approx of ROC, need library {pROC}
  prediction = pred[, "1"]
  category = train$diabetes == "1"
  ROCobj <- roc(category, prediction)
  AUC = auc(ROCobj)
  AUC = round(as.vector(AUC[1]),3)
  ###
  n = length(senspe.mtx[3,])
  idx = which(senspe.mtx[3,] == max(senspe.mtx[3,]))
  tick.label = as.character(round(cut.prob,2))
  ###
  par(mfrow = c(1,2))
  plot(1-senspe.mtx[2,], senspe.mtx[1,], 
       type="l",
       lwd = 2,
       col = "navy",
       xlim=c(0,1), 
       ylim = c(0,1),
       xlab = "1 - specificity", 
       ylab = "Sensitivity", 
       main = "ROC (Taining Data)", 
       cex.main = 0.8)
  # Adding off diagonal line representing random guess
  segments(0, 0, 1, 1, lty = 2, col = "red", )
  legend("bottomright",c("fn = 10", "fp = 1", "cp = 0.02", paste("auc =", AUC)), bty="n", cex = 0.8)       
  
  plot(1:length(cut.prob), senspe.mtx[3,], 
       xlab="cut-off probability",
       ylab = "accuracy", 
       ylim=c(min(senspe.mtx[3,]),1),
       axes = FALSE,
       main="cut-off vs accuracy",
       cex.main = 0.9,
       col.main = "navy")
       # Adding axes and other graphical components to the plot
       axis(1, at=1:20, label = tick.label, las = 2)
       axis(2)
       points(idx, senspe.mtx[3,][idx], pch=19, col = "red")
       segments(idx , min(senspe.mtx[3,]), idx , senspe.mtx[3,][idx ], col = "red")
       #text(idx, senspe.mtx[3,][idx]+0.03, as.character(round(senspe.mtx[3,][idx],4)), 
       #     col = "red", cex = 0.8)
       legend("topright", c(paste("optimal cut-off prob = ",round(median(cut.prob[idx]),3), sep=""), 
                            paste("accuracy = ", round(mean(senspe.mtx[3,][idx ]),3), sep="")),
                          cex = 0.8, bty = "n", adj = -0)

The ROC curve and the plot for optimal cut-off determination

The AUC of the ROC curve for BAGGING is 0.833.

9 Conclusion

We did ROC curves analysis for logistic, perceptron, decision tree, and BAGGING algorithms.

  • The best AUC for logistic model is 0.996.
  • The best AUC for percetron model is 0.9621.
  • The best AUC for decision tree model is 0.97.
  • The best AUC for BAGGING model is 0.834.

The best model via ROC analysis is the logistic model. We need the model that has the highest AUC and the logistic model has the highest AUC: 0.996 out of all the models.

The reduced model is: diabetes ~ age + bmi + blood_glucose_level. The variable of age, BMI and blood glucose level have positive correlation with diabetes. Other variables might be a confounding factors. Therefore, we choose the reduced model that provide us a higher accuracy than the other models. We use the reduced model to predict diabetes, from the full logistic model, we find out that the other predictor variables are also correlated to diabetes. Since our goal is to predict diabetes, we choose the reduced model with higher accuracy.
